Exercise

Consider the plane sheet, or lamina, shown below. In this exercise we will find the location of its centre of mass \((\bar{x}, \bar{y})\).

  1. First, by noting the symmetry of the lamina we can already determine the \(y\) coordinate, \(\bar{y}\), of the centre of mass.

    \(\bar{y} = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]

  2. Let \(\rho\) stand for the mass per unit area of the lamina hence the total area is \(3\) units and the total mass is \(3\rho\). Its moment about the \(y\)-axis is \(3\rho\bar{x}\).

    To find \(\bar{x}\) first divide the lamina into a large number of thin vertical slices. In the figure below a typical slice has been highlighted. Note that the slice has been drawn from the point \(P\) on the line \(y = 3x\). The point \(P\) has coordinates \((x, 3x)\). The thickness of the slice is \(\delta x\). A typical slice of this sheet has been shaded in the left image below.

    Approximate the area of the slice by a rectangle as indicated in the right of the image above.

    Approximate area of slice: [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]

  3. Writing \(\rho\) as the mass per unit area, approximate the mass of the slice using the area from the previous part.

    Note: write rho for \(\rho\).

    Approximate mass of slice: [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]

  4. The centre of mass of this slice lies on the \(x\)-axis. We will take the limit as the thickness approaches zero so the slice can be assumed to be a point mass located a distance \(x\) from \(O\). Write down the approximate moment of the mass of the slice about the \(y\)-axis using the mass above.

  5. Now to consider the moment of the lamina we add up contributions from all such slices in the lamina. Following which we take a limit by letting \(\delta x \to 0\) to obtain the integral:

    \(3\rho\bar{x}=\)

generalfeedback.text:
1. \(\bar{y}=0\) since the lamina is symmetric through reflection in the \(x\)-axis.
  2. The width is \(\delta\) and height \(3x+3x=6x\) so we have \(6x\delta\).
  3. The mass is uniform so we simply have \(\rho \times 6x\delta\).
  4. We are told to take the distance from the \(y\)-axis to the centre of mass of this rectangle to be \(x\) so the moment of inertia is \(x \times 6x\rho\delta = 6x^2\rho\delta\).
  5. The lamina sits above the interval \([0,1]\), taking the limit as \(\delta \rightarrow 0\) give the integral \(\int_{0}^{1}6\rho x^2 dx\)
  6. Evaluating the integral \(\int_{0}^{1}6\rho x^2 dx = \left[2\rho x^3 \right]_{0}^{1} = 2\rho\).

    This must equal the moment of the total mass acting at the centre of mass so \(3\rho\bar{x} = 2\rho\) giving \(\bar{x} =2/3\).

    Now the coordinates of the centre of mass are \((2/3, 0)\).
